trades.notes: Re-entry after being stopped out prior trade. Clear bullish hulk candle. Executed and managed well. Took clean profit at upper VWAP band. Felt good to get something going.

Good trade, good entry. Missed the original bullish hulk candle and took a later stop entry; cleaner if I’d taken original signal. Trade played out, but came back and stopped me at break even. After many losses I wasn’t willing to leave extra risk, so I moved stop to break even.
Adding contracts / adding to position. Same as prior trade. Error—shouldn’t be in this trade at all.
Another bad trade. No setup at all. Forcing trades. Coming close to going on 2.

Good entry signal and good process. But needed to think outside the strategy: long bullish wicks forming on VWAP indicated reversal; fading it wasn’t a high-probability trade. Followed plan, but not a great trade in real conditions.
Again lots of mistakes. Wasn't a clear entry signal. Tried to force the entry. Errors and major deviations from my trading plan.
Good entry, good signal. Volatility made it tricky; price behavior around VWAP hard to judge. Got stuffed out again.
All errors. Not a valid entry signal. Start of a rough session—made a lot of errors and was trying to force trades.
Entry signal wasn’t valid, so the trade wasn’t valid either. Trying to catch bullish momentum bouncing off VWAP. Didn’t work.
Okay trade. Entry signal was okay but it was on the opening candle; trying to catch opening volatility/volume of London. Everything was normal but unfortunately it was a loss.

Was about to finish for the day; spotted strong bullish close above VWAP (continuation from open). Waited for bullish HULK candle close above VWAP and entered, but it wasn’t planned. Took a protected approach (TP ~1.5R). Due to significant volatility in GC and NQ and having already traded well, exited early for small profit. Composure/execution fine; noted “enter again” impulse/greed and that your edge works best with minimal exposure.

Prep was shorter than it should be as I had to drop off the girls at school.

Much like yesterday, although shorter prep, I was still able to recognize an entry signal and execute cleanly.

Before London open, there was a lot of price action around the lower VWAP band, price was struggling to go shorter.

Just after opening, London volume came in and started pushing price bullish, with a clean and strong HULK entry candle that closed above the lower VWAP band.

Placed stop entry, and then managed the trade well.

Had take profit around VWAP, ended up closing slightly early as I felt price becoming quite volatile, and I thought there would be another significant pullback before heading towards TP.

Emotions during the trade were good, kept composed. Perhaps at the end, slight feeling of regret and having missed out on more profit. Just something that I have to keep practicing to overcome.

Late start due to school drop-off delay. Stayed composed and adapted. Noted strong bearish open, then a strong bearish “HULK” candle beyond lower VWAP band suggesting continuation lower toward nearest significant level. Took first entry signal. No overconfidence/over-risking. Executed, managed, and exited to plan. This was the only trade today.

Re-entry (not an “entry to plan”). Saw bullish momentum continuing from prior trade. Entered a smaller contract on a strong bullish Hulk close above the 1-min swing high, targeting upper V1 band. Initial plan: take profits at 5-min swing high. As the trade developed, 5-min closed strongly above upper V1 band and a very large 1-min bullish candle printed, so you switched to letting it run with stop at the clearest level: previous day high. Didn’t want another breakeven stop-out; composure good; good way to finish the day.

Add-on/second contract to the T9 long. Same context: patient wait for bullish signal at VWAP band; added on the follow-through bullish Hulk candle. Aimed for upper VWAP band; retrace led to breakeven stop per plan. Process good.

Price bouncing along VWAP band with lots of resistance/support. Stayed patient waiting for a clear signal. Got two strong bullish “Hulk” candle closes; entered 1 contract on the first, then added a second on the next bullish Hulk candle. Aimed for upper VWAP band; price retraced and stopped out at breakeven per management plan. Overall good trade and process.

Price back across VWAP band, bullish. Clear entry with two bullish “Hulk” candle closes. Entry and management good; composure good. Potential issue: after prior losses you tried to stretch the trade to make back money. Looking left showed heavy resistance at upper VWAP band. TP was set higher (targeting Asia session high); if TP was at upper VWAP band it would have been a full TP. Still ended up banking +2R.

Same context as T6. This trade was adding to the short position (building size). Bearish continuation idea, but market was choppy/range-bound; momentum slowed and reversed. Needed tighter stop-loss/management when momentum slowed, especially while adding.

Bearish gap down looked like strong continuation. Took short; added another contract on a second bearish “Hulk” entry candle. Market stayed range-bound/choppy; momentum slowed and weakened, then reversed. Improvement: tighten stop-loss when momentum slowdown signs appear, especially with the added second contract.

Re-entry after prior stop-out. Lots of price action/resistance around the VWAP band. Nice bullish entry candle with no upper wick; took the entry, but a bit early (didn’t wait for candle close). Continued choppiness around VWAP; stopped out for a loss. Part of the game.

Good entry; adapted quickly after T3 stop-out. Strong signal: bounce off VWATT; expected momentum toward upper VWATT band. Quick retrace after the initial explosion; stopped out just below breakeven. Kept stop tight—if it snaps back fast, you read it as reversal and the trade isn’t working.
Good entry signal. Followed trade management plan. Standard loss; process good. This trade was adding another contract to the existing position to build size (attempt to scale/add).
Good entry signal. Followed trade management plan. Attempted to add another contract but setup didn’t allow it. Standard loss; process good.

reviews.ai_insight:
Week summary: Net +2875 on 81 trades, win rate 49.4%, avg efficiency 0.01 (well below >2.0 target) with -540 cost of errors. Main pattern: profitability is being capped by low efficiency (early exits / not holding to targets) and a recurring emotional chain reaction after feeling 'cheated' or missing profit (early exit/stop -> frustration -> make-up mindset -> forced trades/revenge). Notes also indicate environmental stress/noise contributed to premature exits. When composed, execution aligns with a clear model (momentum/context + structured entry/add + thesis to level). Key focus: interrupt the revenge loop immediately after a perceived injustice and protect the account from tilt-induced drawdown.

Actionable rule: mandatory flat break (e.g., 10 minutes) after any non-model trade, early exit, or 2 losses in a row; reduce size when environment is distracting.
reviews.user_reflection: Up-and-down week with a notable tilt episode on Mon 2025-12-29 leading to significant drawdown (would have been near max daily drawdown on a challenge). Regained composure and traded well afterward. Recognizes ability to make money but must be careful after a couple losses or when feeling missed out/cheated. Intends to lock out, step away, reset, and return composed to reduce leakage on the back end and manage losses properly.

reviews.ai_insight: Stats: 9 trades, Net P/L -120.00, Win rate 33.3%, Avg Efficiency 2.89 (above 2.0 target), Cost of Errors -640.00. Behavioral patterns: (1) Edge shows when you pick best market/setup and execute cleanly (T2 template). (2) Biggest leak was not entries but risk and interference: exposure stacking (ES+NQ) and repeated over-risking (notably T8/T9) led to stop tinkering and trading P/L rather than the trade. (3) Emotional sequencing: after a win or stop-out you pressed (greed/forcing/overconfidence in T4), turning an otherwise fine day into error-cost. Key rule: if you feel over-risked, reduce size or do not trade; over-size reliably triggers micromanagement and collapses edge.
reviews.user_reflection: Noted that early-session greed and subsequent mistakes need to be sat with rather than “pushed for more.” Recognized a repeating pattern over recent sessions: make mistakes/go into drawdown, then over-risk and try to trade out of drawdown instead of stopping to reset and review plan, execution, and composure. Chose to stop for the day to reset. Intends to focus on basics next session: trade smaller (e.g., 1 contract), no stress, take only clear entries, and avoid the mindset of making it back. London session was traded poorly due to lack of prep and not dealing with losses, leading to trying to compensate in NY in a performance sense; wants to be more professional and handle losing properly.

reviews.ai_insight: Week 2025-12-15 to 2025-12-21: Net +1845.00 on 39 trades with 51.3% win rate, but Efficiency Score 0.54 (below 2.0 target) and Cost of Errors -1085.00 show a profitable week achieved with significant self-inflicted leakage. Notes show two modes: when executing well you are patient and let trades work; when impatience appears you force entries without signal, trade chop, and can slide into tilt (notably 2025-12-17: repeated ‘no signal/forced’ entries -> chasing -> breaking session rules -> trading until lockout/DD). Another recurring theme is inconsistency in protection/management when right (hesitation to move stop to BE) and P/L-protection psychology (fear of giving back profits leading to hesitation, then later forcing). Priority is eliminating ‘no-signal’ trades and having pre-decided management rules to prevent the impatience-to-tilt cascade.
reviews.user_reflection: Although I had mistakes and moments of weakness / poor trading etc. I'm glad in the end that I was able to overcome them and end up net positive. So many times previous, I had let negative days affect me so badly that it would just get continually worse - eventually failing multiple challenges etc. Now I feel like I'm really focused on learning to 'lose' so to speak, making mistakes but remembering that they will happen and I just need to focus on being consistent and doing the right things, day in day out. Next week I want to continue this pattern and become even better than last week in terms of composure, execution etc.

reviews.ai_insight: Strong day in process and emotional control: repeated notes of calm, patience, and composure aligned with high efficiency (3.67) and zero cost of errors. You executed a consistent thesis (Asia low) and accepted when the flush didn’t materialize via disciplined BE management. Watch the one potential crack: resizing/adding because “risk wasn’t enough.” Ensure scaling rules are pre-defined rather than emotion-led. Keep using BE as a confirmation-based protection tool, not as discomfort avoidance.
reviews.user_reflection: Thoughts for today follows much of what was said in the trade notes. Felt on point, felt composed and just ready to trade. Not overly emotional. I hope to keep the mind frame and composure for next session, and the session after that. Eventually let it be my baseline and really start getting consistent with my trading.

reviews.ai_insight: Net profitable week but very low efficiency (0.36 vs target >2.0), suggesting overtrading/chop exposure and entries not aligned with core strategy. Notes indicate a pattern: missing an early trade triggers urgency/chasing, followed by repeated stop-outs; awareness of needing to walk away but continuing to trade; and revenge trading rationalized as “confluence.” Key risk is emotional escalation after a losing day leading to TILT and historically large drawdowns/account damage. Primary focus: protect mindset first—implement a mandatory reset protocol after missed trades or first significant emotional spike; prioritize selectivity and execution quality over participation.
reviews.user_reflection: Yes definitely felt this. I have noticed that I can trade ok and be profitable for a few days, even weeks, however I am not trading effciently or inline with my strategy. Then I have a losing day, which typically sets me off and I end up on TILT. Often blowing my account. My goals for next week are to keep composed, keep consistent, focus on execution and being a 'professional trader' who understands the market isn't about winning, its about process, day in day out.
